1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,020
As we start to build out lists,

2

00:00:02,020  -->  00:00:04,940
there will come times where we need to duplicate the result,

3

00:00:04,940  -->  00:00:07,780
while also preserving the original list as well.

4

00:00:07,780  -->  00:00:12,100
Sometimes when we're working with data and we modify the items inside,

5

00:00:12,100  -->  00:00:15,620
we will want to keep that updated list the way that it is,

6

00:00:15,620  -->  00:00:20,360
but then run an experiment or run some computation on it.

7

00:00:20,360  -->  00:00:22,860
In order to do that in a safe manner,

8

00:00:22,860  -->  00:00:27,375
we will want to copy that list Number 1 into a list Number 2,

9

00:00:27,375  -->  00:00:31,740
and then we can use that list Number 2 for a whole bunch of computations.

10

00:00:31,740  -->  00:00:35,475
Let's say that we update list Number 2,

11

00:00:35,475  -->  00:00:38,505
and then it turns out we made a mistake.

12

00:00:38,505  -->  00:00:43,050
Fortunately, for us, we have a whole backup with list Number 1

13

00:00:43,050  -->  00:00:47,450
that we could copy into a list Number 3 and work with that list now,

14

00:00:47,450  -->  00:00:49,410
all things to the copy function.

15

00:00:49,410  -->  00:00:54,065
Let's say some examples of copying and cloning of lists in action.

16

00:00:54,065  -->  00:00:57,430
In order to see copying and cloning in action,

17

00:00:57,430  -->  00:00:59,710
when we think about list comprehensions,

18

00:00:59,710  -->  00:01:04,950
it's helpful to think first about what happens when you assign one list to another.

19

00:01:04,950  -->  00:01:09,750
When this happens, both lists then refer to the same list in memory.

20

00:01:09,750  -->  00:01:12,890
Here's an example to see what this means.

21

00:01:12,890  -->  00:01:16,020
Let's create two lists first,

22

00:01:16,020  -->  00:01:18,765
one for fruits and one for veggies.

23

00:01:18,765  -->  00:01:22,120
Our fruits list will look like this.

24

00:01:22,120  -->  00:01:24,760
Our veggies list will look like this.

25

00:01:24,760  -->  00:01:27,820
In fruits, we have apple, banana, and cherry,

26

00:01:27,820  -->  00:01:30,040
and then for veggies, we have spinach,

27

00:01:30,040  -->  00:01:31,805
lettuce, and bok choy.

28

00:01:31,805  -->  00:01:38,460
Those are three items that are strings in each list fruits and veggies.

29

00:01:40,210  -->  00:01:45,090
We'll execute this code so that it creates these two lists.

30

00:01:45,090  -->  00:01:47,890
If we were to print veggies,

31

00:01:48,930  -->  00:01:51,850
we'll see the output of spinach,

32

00:01:51,850  -->  00:01:53,790
lettuce, and bok choy.

33

00:01:53,790  -->  00:01:58,470
Now, let's at veggies as fruits and print the value of veggies.

34

00:01:58,470  -->  00:02:03,030
We'll say veggies equal fruits.

35

00:02:03,640  -->  00:02:07,285
Then we'll print veggies.

36

00:02:07,285  -->  00:02:10,930
What do you think the output of veggies will now be when we

37

00:02:10,930  -->  00:02:14,265
execute this code? Let's find out.

38

00:02:14,265  -->  00:02:17,030
If we execute this code, we'll see,

39

00:02:17,030  -->  00:02:20,790
veggies is now apple, banana, and cherry,

40

00:02:20,790  -->  00:02:25,050
and the veggies list has been replaced with what the value of the fruits list is.

41

00:02:25,050  -->  00:02:27,430
Veggies now refers to the list of fruits,

42

00:02:27,430  -->  00:02:31,730
which were those three items we had when we initially created the fruits list,

43

00:02:31,730  -->  00:02:34,775
which is apple, banana, and cherry.

44

00:02:34,775  -->  00:02:39,160
If this was a mistake, we can't undo or go backwards,

45

00:02:39,160  -->  00:02:43,020
The list has now been overwritten and changed forever.

46

00:02:43,020  -->  00:02:45,760
To prevent this from happening,

47

00:02:45,760  -->  00:02:48,440
we can leverage the copy function.

48

00:02:48,440  -->  00:02:51,880
Let's recreate these arrays or lists and

49

00:02:51,880  -->  00:02:55,995
try out our new copy function to see how this can help us.

50

00:02:55,995  -->  00:03:00,740
We will copy the lists of fruits and veggies,

51

00:03:00,740  -->  00:03:05,900
and we will execute this code so that we have these lists.

52

00:03:05,900  -->  00:03:08,150
Now, recreate it,

53

00:03:08,150  -->  00:03:12,660
and to make a copy of our veggies list, we'll do something like this.

54

00:03:12,660  -->  00:03:20,800
We'll say veggies, underscore clone equals veggies dot copy,

55

00:03:20,800  -->  00:03:25,620
and we'll assign the copy function to veggies.

56

00:03:25,620  -->  00:03:30,780
We'll then print veggies clone,

57

00:03:30,780  -->  00:03:33,200
and when we run this,

58

00:03:33,200  -->  00:03:37,600
we can see that it's the same items that are in veggies,

59

00:03:37,600  -->  00:03:39,760
which is spinach, lettuce,

60

00:03:39,760  -->  00:03:42,610
and bok choy, as we see up here.

61

00:03:44,070  -->  00:03:47,710
To give this a bit more context about what cloning is,

62

00:03:47,710  -->  00:03:52,930
cloning doesn't mean it's a link to the reference of the list. What does that mean?

63

00:03:52,930  -->  00:03:55,850
Let's see an example where we add a new item to

64

00:03:55,850  -->  00:03:59,820
the veggies list with our newly learned append utility.

65

00:03:59,820  -->  00:04:04,195
If we do veggies.append,

66

00:04:04,195  -->  00:04:07,780
and let's say we add carrot.

67

00:04:07,970  -->  00:04:11,620
When we print veggies,

68

00:04:12,470  -->  00:04:17,910
we'll now see a new vegetable in the output added at the end.

69

00:04:17,910  -->  00:04:19,630
Now it says spinach,

70

00:04:19,630  -->  00:04:22,640
lettuce, bok choy, and carrot.

71

00:04:22,640  -->  00:04:28,850
However, does this mean that the veggies clone updates to? What do you think?

72

00:04:28,850  -->  00:04:33,570
If we were to print veggies clone,

73

00:04:33,570  -->  00:04:36,610
what do you think the output would be?

74

00:04:39,010  -->  00:04:45,930
Let's find out. We see here that veggies clone is spinach,

75

00:04:45,930  -->  00:04:47,615
lettuce, and bok choy.

76

00:04:47,615  -->  00:04:50,130
If you notice, it's missing the new vegetable

77

00:04:50,130  -->  00:04:52,910
that was added to veggies, which was carrot.

78

00:04:52,910  -->  00:04:55,070
This is because when you take a copy,

79

00:04:55,070  -->  00:04:58,790
the new list is a replicate at that point in time.

80

00:04:58,790  -->  00:05:01,830
If we had said, for example,

81

00:05:01,830  -->  00:05:06,810
veggies clone equals veggies.

82

00:05:06,810  -->  00:05:09,650
Instead of what we had before,

83

00:05:09,650  -->  00:05:13,790
which was veggies under scare clone equals veggies copy,

84

00:05:13,790  -->  00:05:16,370
then veggies clone would have been a reference

85

00:05:16,370  -->  00:05:19,850
to the list and then Carrot would have been included.

86

00:05:19,970  -->  00:05:24,480
But we cloned the veggies list before we added carrot.

87

00:05:24,480  -->  00:05:28,530
That's why the veggies clone didn't include that item.

88

00:05:31,520  -->  00:05:36,460
Another way we can clone a list is with the slice method,

89

00:05:36,460  -->  00:05:41,100
which we just learned about in the previous section.

90

00:05:41,100  -->  00:05:43,240
Let's see how this works.

91

00:05:43,240  -->  00:05:46,880
If we want to make a new list called veggies clone

92

00:05:46,880  -->  00:05:50,950
2 and set that equal to veggies, we would do something like this.

93

00:05:50,950  -->  00:05:56,100
We could say veggies_clone2=veggies.

94

00:05:56,690  -->  00:05:59,845
We'll do a square bracket,

95

00:05:59,845  -->  00:06:03,000
colon, and then end square bracket.

96

00:06:03,000  -->  00:06:06,710
When we print veggies_clone2,

97

00:06:08,340  -->  00:06:12,200
what do you think the output will be?

98

00:06:15,440  -->  00:06:18,260
If we execute this code,

99

00:06:18,260  -->  00:06:21,000
we'll see spinach, lettuce,

100

00:06:21,000  -->  00:06:23,000
bok choy, and carrot.

101

00:06:23,000  -->  00:06:29,650
Notice how this new clone now includes the carrot item in the list at the end.

102

00:06:29,650  -->  00:06:32,900
This is because the new cloned list was

103

00:06:32,900  -->  00:06:36,720
made after this last item was added to the veggies array.

104

00:06:36,720  -->  00:06:41,310
Instead of putting numbers around the semi-colon,

105

00:06:41,310  -->  00:06:43,140
which we have here with

106

00:06:43,140  -->  00:06:49,300
square bracket colon square bracket to limit the start and end of the slice method.

107

00:06:49,300  -->  00:06:52,760
If we leave it like this, it will include everything in the list.

108

00:06:52,760  -->  00:06:56,875
This is a crafty shortcut for making a copy in Python.

109

00:06:56,875  -->  00:07:04,140
Just like that, you've learned two very powerful ways to copy lists in Python. Great job.
